# Privacy Policy — PurePage

**Last updated: April 2026**

## Overview

PurePage is a Chrome extension that extracts and displays the main content of web pages in a clean reading view. This policy explains how the extension handles your data.

## Data Collected

PurePage stores the following data **locally in your browser only**:

- Your reading preferences (theme, font style, font size, and CE highlight toggle)
- The most recently extracted article (title, content, byline, and source URL), held temporarily in local storage while the reader view is open

No browsing history, article content, or personal data is retained beyond your current session.

## Data Storage

All data is stored using Chrome's `storage.local` API. It never leaves your browser and is not accessible to any website or third party.

Extracted article content is written to local storage when you open the reader view and is overwritten the next time you use the extension.

## Data Sharing

No data is collected, transmitted, or shared with any external server, service, or third party.

## Third-Party Libraries

PurePage bundles the following open-source libraries:

- **Readability.js** by Mozilla (Apache 2.0) - used to extract article content from pages. It runs entirely within your browser and does not transmit any data.
- **OpenDyslexic** font by Abelardo Gonzalez (SIL OFL 1.1) - an optional font for improved readability.

## Permissions

- **activeTab** - grants temporary access to the current tab when the popup is opened
- **scripting** - used to inject the Readability library into the page to extract article content
- **storage** - used to save your reading preferences and temporarily hold extracted article content

## Changes to This Policy

This policy may be updated occasionally. The latest version will always be available at this URL.

